---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeTabs from '../../../components/CodeTabs.astro';
import { MANUAL_FORCES } from '@fundamental-engine/core';

const cell = `<field-cell force="swirl" color="#2dd4bf"></field-cell>`;

const setup = `<script type="module">
  import '@fundamental-engine/elements';
</script>

<field-root accent="#4da3ff"></field-root>`;

const bodies = `<!-- one force -->
<a data-body="attract" data-strength="0.9" data-range="320">pull me</a>

<!-- composed forces + a condition gate + density write-back -->
<button
  data-body="repel swirl"
  data-strength="1.2"
  data-range="240"
  data-spin="1"
  data-when="active"
  data-feedback
>swirl</button>`;

const methods = `const field = document.querySelector('field-root');

field.scan();                    // after adding/removing [data-body] elements
field.setFormation('wells');     // global field bias
field.setWaveStyle('circular');  // concentric orbits instead of linear waves
field.setWaveCenter({x: 200, y: 300}); // shift orbits center
field.setAttention(true);        // conserved attention (one strength budget)
field.setCausality(true);        // density spills to neighbours
field.setRender('streamlines');  // draw the force field itself
field.setPalette('heatmap');     // swap the accent color template
field.burst(x, y, '#fff');       // a one-shot shove + heat near a point`;
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Fundamental — Web component guide"
  description="Use the <field-root> web component from @fundamental-engine/elements: register it, mark elements as bodies, set attributes, and drive the field through the proxied FieldHandle. Works in any framework or plain HTML."
>
  <header class="docs-hero">
    <p class="kicker">Guides</p>
    <h1>The <span class="accent">web component</span></h1>
    <p class="lede">
      <code>&lt;field-root&gt;</code> is the keystone — a custom element that drops into any
      framework (or plain HTML) unchanged. "Every element is a body" is a web-components-shaped
      idea.
    </p>
  </header>

  <div class="callout">
    <b>An authoring surface, not a separate engine.</b> <code>&lt;field-root&gt;</code> mounts the
    visible field surface and participates in the same Fundamental contracts. DOM-facing behavior belongs
    to the <a href="/docs/api">platform layer</a> — measurement, state, feedback, relationships,
    visual bindings, and overlays — which the element runs by default (Phase D).
  </div>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>Install</h2>
    <div class="pkg">
      <code class="install" data-copy="npm i @fundamental-engine/elements">npm i @fundamental-engine/elements</code>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>Set up the field</h2>
    <p>
      Import the package once to register the element, then drop a single
      <code>&lt;field-root&gt;</code> anywhere. It mounts a fixed, full-viewport canvas behind
      your page and runs the engine. It's decorative, so it marks itself
      <code>aria-hidden</code> automatically.
    </p>
    <CodeTabs variants={[{ label: 'HTML', lang: 'html', code: setup }]} />
  </section>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>Mark elements as bodies</h2>
    <p>
      The field reacts to every <code>[data-body]</code> element on the page (the field-reacts
      law). Forces compose, space-separated; each force reads only the attributes it uses.
    </p>
    <CodeTabs variants={[{ label: 'HTML', lang: 'html', code: bodies }]} />
    <div class="callout">
      <b>Rescan after DOM changes.</b> The engine reads bodies on mount. If you add or remove
      <code>[data-body]</code> elements later (a route change, a list update), call
      <code>field.scan()</code> so it picks them up.
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>Attributes</h2>
    <p>Set these on the <code>&lt;field-root&gt;</code> element:</p>
    <ul class="model">
      <li><b>accent</b> — the travelling accent color (a hex string).</li>
      <li><b>density</b> — particle-count multiplier (default 1).</li>
      <li><b>waves</b> — draw the background Currents (opt-in: add the attribute to enable; absent = off, the bare field).</li>
      <li><b>wave-style</b> — the wave current pattern: <code>linear</code> (default) or <code>circular</code>.</li>
      <li><b>wave-center</b> — custom coordinate string space-separated, e.g. <code>"200 300"</code> (default matches star/vortex bodies or center).</li>
      <li><b>render</b> — <code>dots</code> · <code>trails</code> · <code>links</code> · <code>metaballs</code> · <code>voronoi</code> · <code>streamlines</code>.</li>
      <li><b>depth</b> — optional z-volume (default <code>0</code>, the flat field); <code>&gt; 0</code> opens a shallow depth matter drifts through, projected as a size/alpha recession.</li>
      <li><b>palette</b> — <code>ours</code> · <code>heatmap</code> · <code>infrared</code> · <code>spectrum</code>.</li>
      <li><b>attention</b> — opt into conserved attention (one finite strength budget).</li>
      <li><b>causality</b> — opt into cross-boundary causality (density spills to neighbours).</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Full details in the <a href="/docs/api/options">options reference</a>.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>Methods</h2>
    <p>
      The full <a href="/docs/api/handle">FieldHandle</a> is proxied onto the element, so any
      page can drive the field after it mounts:
    </p>
    <CodeTabs variants={[{ label: 'JavaScript', lang: 'js', code: methods }]} />
  </section>

  <section class="docs-sec">
    <h2>The Field Cell</h2>
    <p>
      For a small, in-frame, single-force demo (instead of the page-wide field), use
      <code>&lt;field-cell&gt;</code> — a container-sized canvas that runs one force with its own
      particle pool. It pauses off-screen (IntersectionObserver), re-fits on resize, and honours
      reduced motion. It's the embeddable unit behind the Manual's per-concept demos.
    </p>
    <CodeTabs variants={[{ label: 'HTML', lang: 'html', code: cell }]} />
    <figure class="force-cell solo" style="--fc:#2dd4bf; margin-top:0.9rem">
      <field-cell force="swirl" color="#2dd4bf" style="height:150px"></field-cell>
      <figcaption>
        <b>swirl</b>
        <span>live — move your cursor through the frame</span>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <div class="callout">
      <b>Supported forces.</b> The cell is a simplified poster engine — it runs
      <code>attract</code>, <code>repel</code>, <code>swirl</code>, <code>gravity</code>,
      <code>stream</code>, <code>buoyancy</code>, and <code>tether</code>. For the full {''}
      <a href="/docs/api/forces">catalog of {MANUAL_FORCES.length}</a> against the canonical math, use the page field
      or <a href="/lab">the Lab</a>.
    </div>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
